<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>10599</anchor> <rss>jms-004T.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004T</addr>  <route>jms-004T.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Univalent deductive system</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <link href="jms-0048.xml" type="local" title="Deductive system">deductive system</link> is called <em>univalent</em> when it is both <link href="jms-004Q.xml" type="local" title="Positively univalent deductive system">positively univalent</link> and <link href="jms-004S.xml" type="local" title="Negatively univalent deductive system">negatively univalent</link>.</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>10600</anchor> <rss>jms-004W.rss.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-004W</addr>  <route>jms-004W.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The univalence condition for deductive systems</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>1</crumb></trail> <anchor>10601</anchor> <rss>jms-004Q.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004Q</addr>  <route>jms-004Q.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Positively univalent deductive system</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <link href="jms-0048.xml" type="local" title="Deductive system">deductive system</link> <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> is called <em>positively univalent</em> when for any positive <tex>A \in \mathcal {D}</tex>, the type of positive objects <tex>B \in \mathcal {D}</tex> equipped with a <link href="jms-004R.xml" type="local" title="Thunkably and linearly invertible maps">thunkably invertible</link> <link href="jms-004A.xml" type="local" title="Linear and thunkable maps">thunkable</link> map <tex>f:B \vdash  A</tex> is contractible.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>2</crumb></trail> <anchor>10602</anchor> <rss>jms-004S.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004S</addr>  <route>jms-004S.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Negatively univalent deductive system</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <link href="jms-0048.xml" type="local" title="Deductive system">deductive system</link> <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> is called <em>negatively univalent</em> when for any negative <tex>A \in \mathcal {D}</tex>, the type of negative objects <tex>B \in \mathcal {D}</tex> equipped with a <link href="jms-004R.xml" type="local" title="Thunkably and linearly invertible maps">linearly invertible</link> <link href="jms-004A.xml" type="local" title="Linear and thunkable maps">linear</link> map <tex>f:B \vdash  A</tex> is contractible.</p></mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></context> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>10603</anchor> <rss>jms-004S.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004S</addr>  <route>jms-004S.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Negatively univalent deductive system</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <link href="jms-0048.xml" type="local" title="Deductive system">deductive system</link> <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> is called <em>negatively univalent</em> when for any negative <tex>A \in \mathcal {D}</tex>, the type of negative objects <tex>B \in \mathcal {D}</tex> equipped with a <link href="jms-004R.xml" type="local" title="Thunkably and linearly invertible maps">linearly invertible</link> <link href="jms-004A.xml" type="local" title="Linear and thunkable maps">linear</link> map <tex>f:B \vdash  A</tex> is contractible.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>10604</anchor> <rss>jms-004Q.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004Q</addr>  <route>jms-004Q.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Positively univalent deductive system</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <link href="jms-0048.xml" type="local" title="Deductive system">deductive system</link> <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> is called <em>positively univalent</em> when for any positive <tex>A \in \mathcal {D}</tex>, the type of positive objects <tex>B \in \mathcal {D}</tex> equipped with a <link href="jms-004R.xml" type="local" title="Thunkably and linearly invertible maps">thunkably invertible</link> <link href="jms-004A.xml" type="local" title="Linear and thunkable maps">thunkable</link> map <tex>f:B \vdash  A</tex> is contractible.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>10605</anchor> <rss>jms-0048.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-0048</addr>  <route>jms-0048.xml</route> <date><year>2022</year> <month>12</month> <day>25</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Deductive system</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A deductive system <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> is given by a type <tex>\mathbf {ob} _{ \mathcal {D} }</tex> of “objects”, and for every pair <tex>A,B \in \mathbf {ob} _{ \mathcal {D} }</tex> a set <tex>\mathbf {hom} _{ \mathcal {D} } { \mathopen {} \left ( A , B \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> of <em>morphisms</em>, together with cut and identity laws:</p><ol><li><strong>cut:</strong> for each <tex>A,B,C \in \mathbf {ob} _{ \mathcal {D} }</tex> and <tex>f \in   \mathbf {hom} _{ \mathcal {D} } { \mathopen {} \left ( A , B \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> and <tex>g \in \mathbf {hom} _{ \mathcal {D} } { \mathopen {} \left ( B , C \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex>, a morphism <tex>f;g \in \mathbf {hom} _{ \mathcal {D} } { \mathopen {} \left ( A , C \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex>.</li>
  
  <li><strong>identity:</strong> for each <tex>A \in \mathbf {ob} _{ \mathcal {D} }</tex>, a morphism <tex>1 _{ A } \in \mathbf {hom} _{ \mathcal {D} } { \mathopen {} \left ( A , A \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> such that <tex>1 _{ A } ;f = f</tex> and <tex>f;1 _{ B }</tex> for each <tex>f \in \mathbf {hom} _{ \mathcal {D} } { \mathopen {} \left ( A , B \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex>.</li></ol></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>10606</anchor> <rss>jms-0051.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Observation</taxon> <addr>jms-0051</addr>  <route>jms-0051.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>An alternative definition of duploids</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Equivalently, we can define a <link href="jms-0050.xml" type="local" title="Duploid">duploid</link> to be a <link href="jms-004T.xml" type="local" title="Univalent deductive system">univalent</link> <link href="jms-004F.xml" type="local" title="Preduploid">preduploid</link> such that every object is <em>merely equipped with</em> both an <link href="jms-004M.xml" type="local" title="Upshift structure">upshift</link> and a <link href="jms-004P.xml" type="local" title="Downshift structure">downshift</link>.</p><p>To see that the <link href="jms-0050.xml" type="local" title="Duploid">main definition</link> implies our alternative definition, let <tex>A</tex> be an object of the preduploid; because we are proving that <tex>A</tex> is <em>merely equipped with</em> both an <link href="jms-004M.xml" type="local" title="Upshift structure">upshift</link> and a <link href="jms-004P.xml" type="local" title="Downshift structure">downshift</link>, we may proceed by cases on the <link href="jms-0045.xml" type="local" title="Polarized object">polarization</link> of <tex>A</tex>.</p><ol><li>If <tex>A</tex> is <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" title="Positive and negative objects">positive</link>, we choose the identity map <tex>A \vdash  A</tex> for the downshift and we use our assumption to deduce that <tex>A</tex> has an upshift.</li>
  <li>If <tex>A</tex> is <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" title="Positive and negative objects">negative</link>, we choose the identity map <tex>A \vdash  A</tex> for the upshift and we use our assumption to deduce that <tex>A</tex> has a downshift.</li></ol>
  
    <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline> 
  <p>Conversely, assume that every object is merely equipped with both an upshift and a downshift. That a positive object <tex>P</tex> has an upshift <link href="jms-004X.xml" type="local" title="Uniqueness of upshifts">is a proposition</link>, so we can use our assumption that <tex>P</tex> <em>merely</em> has an upshift. That a negative object <tex>N</tex> has a downshift <link href="jms-004Z.xml" type="local" title="Uniqueness of downshifts">is likewise a proposition</link>, so we can use our assumption that <tex>N</tex> <em>merely</em> has a downshift.</p>
</block>
  
</mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>10607</anchor> <rss>jms-0050.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-0050</addr>  <route>jms-0050.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Duploid</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <link href="jms-004F.xml" type="local" title="Preduploid">preduploid</link> <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> is called a <em>duploid</em> when it satisfies the following properties:</p><ol><li>the preduploid <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> is <link href="jms-004T.xml" type="local" title="Univalent deductive system">univalent</link>;</li>
  <li>every <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" title="Positive and negative objects">positive</link> object of <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> <link href="jms-004X.xml" type="local" title="Uniqueness of upshifts">has an upshift</link>;</li>
  <li>every <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" title="Positive and negative objects">negative</link> object of <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> <link href="jms-004Z.xml" type="local" title="Uniqueness of downshifts">has a downshift</link>.</li></ol></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>